# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: asteroid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] 101955 Bennu has a mean diameter of 490 m (1,610 ft; 0.30 mi) and has been observed extensively by the Arecibo Observatory planetary radar and the Goldstone Deep Space Network.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Bennu was the target of the OSIRIS-REx mission that returned samples of the asteroid to Earth.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The spacecraft, launched in September 2016, arrived at the asteroid two years later and mapped its surface in detail, seeking potential sample collection sites.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Analysis of the orbits allowed calculation of Bennu's mass and its distribution.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] In October 2020, OSIRIS-REx briefly touched down and collected a sample of the asteroid's surface.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] A capsule containing the sample was returned and landed on Earth in September 2023, with distribution and analysis of the sample ongoing.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] On 15 May 2024, an overview of preliminary analytical studies on the returned samples was reported.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Bennu was discovered on 11 September 1999 during a Near-Earth asteroid survey by the Lincoln Near-Earth Asteroid Research (LINEAR).
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The asteroid was given the provisional designation 1999 RQ36 and classified as a near-Earth asteroid.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Bennu was observed extensively by the Arecibo Observatory and the Goldstone Deep Space Network using radar imaging as Bennu closely approached Earth on 23 September 1999.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The name *Bennu* was selected from more than eight thousand student entries from dozens of countries around the world who entered a "Name that Asteroid!" contest run by the University of Arizona, The Planetary Society, and the LINEAR Project in 2012.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Third-grade student Michael Puzio from North Carolina proposed the name in reference to the Egyptian mythological bird Bennu.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] To Puzio, the OSIRIS-REx spacecraft with its extended TAGSAM arm resembled the Egyptian deity, which is typically depicted as a heron.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Its features are named after birds and bird-like creatures in mythology.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Bennu has a roughly spheroidal shape, resembling a spinning top.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Bennu's axis of rotation is tilted 178 degrees to its orbit; the direction of rotation about its axis is retrograde with respect to its orbit.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The boulders contain veins of high albedo carbonate minerals believed to have formed prior to the formation of the asteroid due to hot water channels on the much larger parent body.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The veins range from 3 to 15 centimeters wide, and can be over one meter in length, much bigger than carbonate veins seen in meteorites.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] An analysis published in 2026 of "spacecraft observations revealed that Bennu is blanketed by boulders of differing physical properties" and implying "cracks in rocks resulting from geological processes within the parent body or, more recently, micrometeoroid impacts and thermal fatigue".
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] There is a well-defined ridge along the equator of Bennu.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The presence of this ridge suggests that fine-grained regolith particles have accumulated in this area, possibly because of its low gravity and fast rotation (about once every 4.3 hours).
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Observation by the OSIRIS-REx spacecraft has shown that Bennu is rotating faster over time.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] This change in Bennu's rotation is caused by the Yarkovsky–O'Keefe–Radzievskii–Paddack effect.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Due to the uneven emission of thermal radiation from its surface as Bennu rotates in sunlight, the rotation period of Bennu decreases by about one second every 100 years.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Observations of this minor planet by the Spitzer Space Telescope in 2007 gave an effective diameter of 484±10 m, which is in line with other studies.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] It has a low visible geometric albedo of 0.046±0.005.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The thermal inertia was measured and found to vary by approximately 19% during each rotational period.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] It was based on this observation that scientists (incorrectly) estimated a moderate regolith grain size, ranging from several millimeters up to a centimeter, evenly distributed.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] No emission from a potential dust coma has been detected around Bennu, which puts a limit of 106 g of dust within a radius of 4750 km.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Astrometric observations between 1999 and 2013 have demonstrated that 101955 Bennu is influenced by the Yarkovsky effect, causing the semimajor axis of its orbit to drift on average by 284±1.5 meters/year.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Analysis of the gravitational and thermal effects has given a bulk density of ρ = 1190±13 kg/m3, which is only slightly denser than water.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Therefore, the predicted macroporosity is 40±10%, suggesting the interior has a rubble pile structure or even hollows.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The sample of Bennu revealed that some of the makings of living things are present on Bennu.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Photometric observations of Bennu in 2005 yielded a synodic rotation period of 4.2905±0.0065 h.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] It has a B-type classification, which is a sub-category of carbonaceous asteroids.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Polarimetric observations show that Bennu belongs to the rare F subclass of carbonaceous asteroids, which is usually associated with cometary features.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Measurements over a range of phase angles showed a phase function slope of 0.040 magnitudes per degree, which is similar to other near-Earth asteroids with low albedo.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Before OSIRIS-REx, spectroscopy indicated a correspondence with the CI and/or CM carbonaceous chondrite meteorites, including carbonaceous-chondrite mineral magnetite.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Magnetite, a spectrally prominent water product but destroyed by heat, is an important proxy of astronomers including OSIRIS-REx staff.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] According to Dante Lauretta, OSIRIS-REx Principal Investigator, "Bennu appears to be a very water-rich target, and water is the most interesting and perhaps the most lucrative commodity that you would mine from an asteroid".
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Predicted beforehand, Dante Lauretta (University of Arizona) reiterates that Bennu is water-rich already detectable while OSIRIS-REx was still technically in approach.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Preliminary spectroscopic surveys of the asteroid's surface by OSIRIS-REx confirmed magnetite and the meteorite-asteroid linkage, dominated by phyllosilicates.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Phyllosilicates, among others, hold water.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Bennu's water spectra were detectable on approach, reviewed by outside scientists, then confirmed from orbit.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] OSIRIS-REx observations have resulted in a (self-styled) conservative estimate of about 7 × 108 kg water in one form alone, neglecting additional forms.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] This is a water content of ~1 wt.%, and potentially much more.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] In turn this suggests transient pockets of water beneath Bennu's regolith.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The surficial water may be lost from the collected samples.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] However, if the sample return capsule maintains low temperatures, the largest (centimeter-scale) fragments may contain measurable quantities of adsorbed water, and some fraction of Bennu's ammonium compounds.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] A separate estimate, including other forms of water storage, is 6.2 wt%.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] NASA and university sample facilities are preparing to secure, study, and curate the sample, predicted to be rich in water and organic compounds.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The German SAL (Sample Analysis Laboratory) is preparing to receive cosmochemical water from Ryugu, Bennu, and other airless bodies.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Bennu is an active asteroid, sporadically emitting plumes of particles and rocks as large as 10 cm (3.9 in) (not dust, defined as tens of micrometers).
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Scientists hypothesize the releases may be caused by thermal fracturing, volatile release through dehydration of phyllosilicates, pockets of subsurface water, and/or meteoroid impacts.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Before the arrival of OSIRIS-REx, Bennu had displayed polarization consistent with Comet Hale-Bopp and 3200 Phaethon, a rock comet.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Bennu, Phaethon, and inactive Manx comets are examples of active asteroids.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] B-type asteroids displaying a blue color in particular, may be dormant comets, similar to Ryugu but at an earlier stage.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] If the IAU declares Bennu to be a dual-status object, its comet designation would be P/1999 RQ36 (LINEAR).
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The Nightingale sample site imaged by OSIRIS-REx at touchdown.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] All geological features on Bennu are named after various species of birds and bird-like figures in mythology.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The first features to be named were the final four candidate OSIRIS-REx sample sites, which were given unofficial names by the team in August 2019.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] On 6 March 2020 the IAU announced the first official names for 12 Bennu surface features, including regiones (broad geographic regions), craters, dorsa (ridges), fossae (grooves or trenches) and saxa (rocks and boulders).
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] After a thorough analysis of Bennu's surface by the OSIRIS-REx mission team, using data from both MapCam and OVIRS, four candidate sites were selected for sample collection: Nightingale, Kingfisher, Osprey, and Sandpiper.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Among these, Nightingale was ultimately chosen, as it exhibited a stronger spectral reddening compared to the rest of the surface (indicating fresher or less exposed terrain).
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Additionally, it successfully passed the safety assessment tests for the spacecraft's descent.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] On 12 December 2019, after a year of mapping Bennu's surface, a target site was announced.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Named Nightingale, the area is near Bennu's north pole and lies inside a small crater within a larger crater.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Osprey was selected as the backup sample site.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The carbonaceous material that composes Bennu came from the breakup of a much larger parent body—a minor planet or a proto-planet.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] It is thought to be a rubble pile of the second generation or later, formed within the past 65 million years.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Like nearly all matter in the Solar System, its atoms were created in dying stars.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] According to the accretion theory, this material came together 4.5 billion years ago during the formation of the Solar System.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Bennu probably began in the inner asteroid belt as a fragment from a larger body with a diameter of 100 km (62 mi).
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Simulations suggest that it came from either the Polana or Eulalia subdivisions of the Nysa-Polana complex, with a 70% chance it came from the Polana family and a 30% chance it derived from the Eulalia family.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Impactors on boulders of Bennu indicate that Bennu has been in near Earth orbit (separated from the main asteroid belt) for 1–2.5 million years.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Subsequently, the orbit drifted as a result of the Yarkovsky effect and mean motion resonances with the giant planets, such as Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Various interactions with the planets in combination with the Yarkovsky effect modified the asteroid, possibly changing its spin, shape, and surface features.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Cellino et al. have suggested a possible cometary origin for Bennu, based on similarities of its spectroscopic properties with known comets.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The estimated fraction of comets in the population of near Earth objects is 8%±5%.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] This includes rock comet 3200 Phaethon, discovered and still numbered as an asteroid.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Bennu orbits the Sun with a period of 1.19 years (435 days) as of 2022.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Earth gets as close as about 480,000 km (0.0032 au) from its orbit around 23 to 25 September.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] On 22 September 1999 Bennu passed 0.0147 au from Earth, and six years later on 20 September 2005 it passed 0.033 au from Earth.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The next close approaches of less than 0.04 au will be 30 September 2054 and then 23 September 2060, which will perturb the orbit slightly.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Between the close approach of 1999 and that of 2060, Earth completes 61 orbits and Bennu 51.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] An even closer approach will occur on 25 September 2135 around 0.0014 au (see table).
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] In the 75 years between the 2060 and 2135 approaches, Bennu completes 64 orbits, meaning its period will have changed to 1.17 years (427 days).
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The Earth approach of 2135 will increase the orbital period to about 1.24 years (452 days).
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Before the 2135 Earth approach, Bennu will be at its maximum distance from Earth on 27 November 2045 at a distance of 2.34 AU (350 million km).
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] On average, an asteroid with a diameter of 500 m (1,600 ft; 0.31 mi) can be expected to impact Earth about every 130,000 years.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] A 2010 dynamical study by Andrea Milani and collaborators predicted a series of eight potential Earth impacts by Bennu between 2169 and 2199.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The cumulative probability of impact is dependent on physical properties of Bennu that were poorly known at the time, but was found to not exceed 0.071% for all eight encounters.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The authors recognized that an accurate assessment of 101955 Bennu's probability of Earth impact would require a detailed shape model and additional observations (either from the ground or from spacecraft visiting the object) to determine the magnitude and direction of the Yarkovsky effect.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The publication of the shape model and of astrometry based on radar observations obtained in 1999, 2005, and 2011 made possible an improved estimate of the Yarkovsky acceleration and a revised assessment of the impact probability.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] In 2014, the best estimate of the impact probability was a cumulative probability of 0.037% in the interval 2175 to 2196.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] This corresponds to a cumulative rating on the Palermo scale of −1.71.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The 2021 orbit solution extended the virtual impactors from the year 2200 to the year 2300 and slightly increased the cumulative Palermo impact hazard scale rating to −1.42.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The solution included the estimated gravitational effect of 343 other asteroids, representing about 90% of the total mass of the main asteroid belt.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Bennu will pass 0.005 au (750,000 km; 460,000 mi) from Earth on 23 September 2060, while for comparison the Moon's average orbital distance (*lunar distance)* is 384,402 km (238,856 mi) and will only change to 384,404 km in 50 years.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Bennu will be too dim to be seen with common binoculars.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The close approach of 2060 causes divergence in the close approach of 2135.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] There is no chance of an Earth impact in 2135.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The 2135 approach will create many lines of variations and Bennu may pass through a gravitational keyhole during the 2135 passage which could create an impact scenario at a future encounter.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The keyholes are all less than ~20 km wide with some keyholes being only 5 meters wide.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The most threatening virtual impactor is on Tuesday, 24 September 2182 when there is a 1 in 2,700 chance of an Earth impact, but the asteroid could be as far as the Sun is from Earth.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] To impact Earth on 24 September 2182 Bennu must pass through a keyhole roughly 5 km wide on 25 September 2135.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] There is a cumulative 1 in 1,800 chance of an Earth impact between 2178 and 2290.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] As an active asteroid with a small minimum orbit intersection distance from Earth, Bennu may be the parent body of a weak meteor shower.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Bennu particles would radiate around 25 September from the southern constellation of Sculptor.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The meteors are expected to be near the naked eye visibility limit and only produce a Zenith hourly rate of less than 1.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The OSIRIS-REx mission of NASA's New Frontiers program was launched towards 101955 Bennu on 8 September 2016.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] On 3 December 2018, the spacecraft arrived at the asteroid Bennu after a two-year journey.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] One week later, at the American Geophysical Union Fall Meeting, investigators announced that OSIRIS-REx had discovered spectroscopic evidence for hydrated minerals on the surface of the asteroid, implying that liquid water was present in Bennu's parent body before it split off.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] On 20 October 2020, OSIRIS-REx descended to the asteroid and "pogo-sticked off" it while successfully collecting a sample.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] On 7 April 2021, OSIRIS-REx completed its final flyover of the asteroid and began slowly drifting away from it.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] On 10 May 2021, the departure was completed with OSIRIS-REx still managing to contain the asteroid sample.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] OSIRIS-REx returned samples to Earth in 2023 via a capsule-drop by parachute, ultimately, from the spacecraft to the Earth's surface in Utah on 24 September 2023.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Shortly after the sample container was retrieved and transferred to an airtight chamber at the Johnson Space Center in Houston, Texas, the lid on the container was opened.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Scientists commented that they "found black dust and debris on the avionics deck of the OSIRIS-REx science canister" on the initial opening.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] On 11 October 2023, the recovered capsule was opened to reveal a "first look" at the asteroid sample contents.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] On 13 December 2023, further studies of the returned sample were reported and revealed organic molecules as well as unknown materials which require more study to have a better idea of their composition and makeup.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] On 11 January 2024, NASA reported finally fully opening, after three months of trying, the recovered container with samples from the Bennu asteroid.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The total weight of the recovered material weighed 121.6 g (4.29 oz), over twice the mission's goal.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The asteroid Bennu was selected from over half a million known asteroids by the OSIRIS-REx selection committee.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The primary constraint for selection was close proximity to Earth, since proximity implies low impulse (Δv) required to reach an object from Earth orbit.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The criteria stipulated an asteroid in an orbit with low eccentricity, low inclination, and an orbital radius of 0.8–1.6 au.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Furthermore, the candidate asteroid for a sample-return mission must have loose regolith on its surface, which implies a diameter greater than 200 meters.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Asteroids smaller than this typically spin too fast to retain dust or small particles.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Finally, a desire to find an asteroid with pristine carbon material from the early Solar System, possibly including volatile molecules and organic compounds, reduced the list further.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] With the above criteria applied, five asteroids remained as candidates for the OSIRIS-REx mission, and Bennu was chosen, in part for its potentially hazardous orbit.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The OSIRIS-REx mission successfully returned approximately 120 grams of material from Bennu to Earth in September 2023.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The returned material is predominantly very dark, with reflectance values consistent with observations of Bennu's surface, though it contains some brighter inclusions and particles.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Particle sizes in the sample span a wide range, from submicron dust to rocks measuring about 3.5 cm in length.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Mineralogical analysis shows that the sample is rich in hydrated minerals, particularly Mg-rich phyllosilicates, confirming predictions from remote sensing data.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Other major components include magnetite, sulfides, carbonates, and organic compounds.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] An unexpected discovery was the presence of phosphate minerals in some samples, including Mg, Na-rich phosphates found as veins and crusts in some particles.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The elemental composition of the Bennu samples closely resembles that of CI chondrite meteorites.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] However, the Bennu material shows some distinct isotopic ratios.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The average oxygen isotopic composition places Bennu in the same region of oxygen three-isotope space as CI and CY chondrites, as well as samples from asteroid Ryugu.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The carbon content of the samples (4.5–4.7 wt%) is higher than that found in known meteorites and Ryugu samples.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] The presence of presolar grains in the samples indicates that some of the material has remained largely unprocessed since the formation of the solar system.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Presolar silicon carbide and graphite were identified, with abundances of 52+12 −10 ppm and 12+7 −5 ppm respectively, similar to unheated chondrite samples.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Evidence suggests that the samples come from at least two different lithologies on Bennu's surface.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Three predominant types of particles were identified: hummocky, angular, and mottled.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] These show distinct densities, with hummocky particles having the lowest average density (1.55±0.07 g/cm3) and mottled particles the highest (1.77±0.04 g/cm3).
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Spectral analysis of the samples shows a redder slope from 0.4 to 2.5 μm compared to Bennu's global spectrum, potentially indicating differences in particle size, surface texture, or space weathering between the sampled material and the asteroid's surface.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Since 3 November 2023, a part of the sample is exhibited at the Hall of Meteorites of the National Museum of Natural History (Washington, DC).
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Another portion of the sample was exhibited by NASA at the International Astronautical Congress in Milan, Italy, from 14 to 18 October 2024.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] In January 2025, it was reported that a wide range of carbon- and nitrogen-rich organic compounds were identified in samples returned from Bennu, including all five nucleobases (adenine, thymine, cytosine, guanine, and uracil) that are the essential building blocks of DNA and RNA.
[src:asteroid/101955-bennu] Fourteen of the 20 amino acids that make up proteins in terrestrial organisms were also present, but unlike the amino acids found in organisms on Earth, the amino acids from Bennu had mixed chirality.
[src:asteroid/185105-2006-sv23-p01] The following is a partial list of minor planets, running from minor-planet number 185001 through 186000, inclusive.
[src:asteroid/185105-2006-sv23-p01] The primary data for this and other partial lists is based on JPL's "Small-Body Orbital Elements" and data available from the Minor Planet Center.
[src:asteroid/185105-2006-sv23-p01] Critical list information is also provided by the MPC, unless otherwise specified from Lowell Observatory.
[src:asteroid/185105-2006-sv23-p01] A detailed description of the table's columns and additional sources are given on the main page including a complete list of every page in this series, and a statistical break-up on the dynamical classification of minor planets.
[src:asteroid/185105-2006-sv23-p01] Also see the summary list of all named bodies in numerical and alphabetical order, and the corresponding naming citations for the number range of this particular list.
[src:asteroid/185105-2006-sv23-p01] New namings may only be added to this list after official publication, as the preannouncement of names is condemned by the Working Group for Small Bodies Nomenclature of the International Astronomical Union.
[src:asteroid/185105-2006-sv23-p02] J. van Houten, I. van Houten-Groeneveld, T.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] 1950 DA was first discovered on 23 February 1950 by Carl A.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] It was observed for seventeen days and then lost because this short observation arc resulted in large uncertainties in Wirtanen's orbital solution.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] On 31 December 2000, it was recovered at Lowell Observatory and was announced as 2000 YK66 on 4 January 2001.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] Just two hours later it was recognized as 1950 DA.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] It was studied by radar at the Goldstone and Arecibo observatories from March 3 to 7, 2001.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] The studies showed that the asteroid has a mean diameter of 1.1 km, assuming that 1950 DA is a retrograde rotator.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] Optical lightcurve analysis by Lenka Šarounová and Petr Pravec shows that its rotation period is 2.1216±0.0001 hours.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] Due to its short rotation period and high radar albedo, 1950 DA is thought to be fairly dense (more than 3.5 g/cm3, assuming that it has no internal strength) and likely composed of nickel–iron.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] In August 2014, scientists from the University of Tennessee determined that 1950 DA is a rubble pile rotating faster than the breakup limit for its density, implying the asteroid is held together by van der Waals forces rather than gravity.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] 1950 DA made distant approaches to Earth on 20 May 2012, 5 February 2021 and 5 February 2023.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] However, at these times it was a quarter to half an AU away from Earth, preventing more useful astrometrics and timing that occurs when an object is closer to Earth.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] The next close approach that presents a good opportunity to observe the asteroid will be on 2 March 2032, when it will be 0.076 AU (11.4 million km) from Earth.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] The following table lists the approaches closer than 0.1 AU until the year 2500.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] By 2136 the close approach solutions are becoming notably more divergent.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] 1950 DA has one of the best-determined asteroid orbital solutions.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] At that distance and size, Diana will perturb 1950 DA enough so that the change in trajectory is notable by 2880 (730 years later).
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] In addition, over the intervening time, 1950 DA's rotation will cause its orbit to slightly change as a result of the Yarkovsky effect.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] If 1950 DA continues on its present orbit, it may approach Earth on 16 March 2880, though the mean trajectory passes many millions of kilometres from Earth, so 1950 DA does not have a significant chance of impacting Earth.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] As of September 2025, according to the latest solution dated 11 September 2025, the probability of an impact in 2880 is 1 in 2,600 (0.038%).
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] The energy released by a collision with an object the size of 1950 DA would cause major effects on the climate and biosphere, which would be devastating to human civilization.
[src:asteroid/29075-1950-da] The discovery of the potential impact heightened interest in asteroid deflection strategies.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] 2006 VW139 was discovered on 15 November 2006, by the Spacewatch survey at Kitt Peak National Observatory near Tucson, Arizona.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] The possible cometary activity was seen in November 2011 by Pan-STARRS.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] Both Spacewatch and Pan-STARRS are asteroid survey projects of NASA's Near Earth Object Observations Program.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] After the Pan-STARRS observations it was also given a comet designation of 288P.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] 2006 VW139 is a non-family asteroid of the main-belt's background population.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] It is both a binary asteroid and a main-belt comet, also known as "active asteroid".
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] It orbits the Sun in the outer main-belt at a distance of 2.4–3.7 AU once every 5 years and 4 months (1,944 days; semi-major axis of 3.05 AU).
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] Its orbit has an eccentricity of 0.20 and an inclination of 3° with respect to the ecliptic.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] The body's observation arc begins in September 2000, with a precovery taken by the Sloan Digital Sky Survey at Apache Point Observatory, New Mexico, more than six years prior to its official discovery observation by Spacewatch at Kitt Peak.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] 2006 VW139 was first observed by the Hubble Space Telescope (HST) in December 2011.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] It was imaged by HST in September 2016, just before it made its closest approach to the Sun and confirmed its binary nature with two asteroids orbiting each other, and revealed ongoing cometary activity.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] This makes the object the first known binary asteroid that is also classified as a main-belt comet.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] The binary is thought to be the result of fission of the precursor caused by YORP-driven spinup.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] Observations of the HST revealed ongoing activity in this binary system.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] The combined features of this binary asteroid - wide separation, near-equal component size, high eccentricity orbit, and comet-like activity also make it unique among the few known binary asteroids that have a wide separation.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] 2006 VW139 has a derived diameter of 1.8±0.2 kilometer.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] The *Collaborative Asteroid Lightcurve Link* assumes an albedo of 0.057 and calculates a diameter of 3.20 kilometers based on an absolute magnitude of 16.2.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] The binary system has an estimated mass between 1.3×1012 kg and 1.1×1013 kg.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] A single component has a derived mass of (6.15±4.85)×1012 kg.
[src:asteroid/300163-2006-vw139] This minor planet was numbered by the Minor Planet Center on 12 October 2011 (M.P.C.
[src:asteroid/419624-2010-so16] The orbit was described by Apostolos Christou and David Asher at the Armagh Observatory in Northern Ireland.
[src:asteroid/419624-2010-so16] The object has an absolute magnitude of 20.5.
[src:asteroid/419624-2010-so16] Observations by the discovering WISE telescope give a diameter of 357 meters and an albedo of 0.084.
[src:asteroid/419624-2010-so16] 2010 SO16 has a horseshoe orbit that allows it to stably share Earth's orbital neighborhood without colliding with it.
[src:asteroid/419624-2010-so16] It is one of a handful of known asteroids with an Earth-following orbit, a group that includes 3753 Cruithne, and the only known asteroid in an horseshoe orbit with Earth.
[src:asteroid/419624-2010-so16] It is, however, neither an Aten asteroid nor an Apollo asteroid because the semi-major axis of its orbit is neither less than nor greater than 1 AU, but oscillates between approximately 0.996 and 1.004 AU, with a period of about 350 years.
[src:asteroid/419624-2010-so16] In its ~350 yr horseshoe cycle, it never approaches Earth more closely than about 0.15 AU, alternately trailing and leading.
[src:asteroid/419624-2010-so16] According to various simulations 2010 SO16 will remain in this orbit for at least 120,000 years and possibly for more than a million years, which is unusually stable compared to other similar objects.
[src:asteroid/419624-2010-so16] One reason for this stability is its low orbital eccentricity, $<0.084$ .
[src:asteroid/419624-2010-so16] A precovery of 2010 SO16 may have been located in a 2005 Spitzer Space Telescope image.
[src:asteroid/457175-2008-go98] 2008 GO98 is classified as a member of the dynamical Hilda group, as well as a Jupiter family that shows clear cometary activity, which has also been described as a "quasi-Hilda comet".
[src:asteroid/457175-2008-go98] Orbital backward integration suggests that it might have been a centaur or trans-Neptunian object that ended its dynamical evolution as a quasi-Hilda comet.
[src:asteroid/457175-2008-go98] It may have reached the belt during the last few hundred years.
[src:asteroid/457175-2008-go98] It orbits the Sun in the outer asteroid belt at a distance of 2.9–5.1 AU once every 7 years and 11 months (2,883 days; semi-major axis of 3.96 AU).
[src:asteroid/457175-2008-go98] Its orbit has an eccentricity of 0.28 and an inclination of 16° with respect to the ecliptic.
[src:asteroid/457175-2008-go98] The body's observation arc begins with a precovery taken by the Sloan Digital Sky Survey in October 2001, more than 5 years prior to its official discovery observation by Spacewatch.
[src:asteroid/457175-2008-go98] Although 2008 GO98 orbits in the asteroid belt, it has a Jupiter Tisserand's parameter (TJ) of 2.926, just below Jewitt's threshold of 3, which serves as a distinction between the main-belt asteroids (TJ larger than 3) and the Jupiter-family comets (TJ between 2 and 3).
[src:asteroid/457175-2008-go98] This minor planet was numbered by the Minor Planet Center on 16 February 2016 (M.P.C.
[src:asteroid/457175-2008-go98] 2008 GO98 is an assumed C-type asteroid.
[src:asteroid/457175-2008-go98] In August 2017, a rotational lightcurve of 2008 GO98 was obtained from photometric observations by American astronomer Brian Warner at the Palmer Divide Station (U82) in California.
[src:asteroid/457175-2008-go98] Lightcurve analysis gave a rotation period of 10.74±0.01 hours with a small brightness amplitude of 0.12 magnitude (U=2).
[src:asteroid/457175-2008-go98] The *Collaborative Asteroid Lightcurve Link* assumes a standard albedo for a carbonaceous body of 0.057 and calculates a diameter of 14.64 kilometers based on an absolute magnitude of 12.9.
[src:asteroid/457175-2008-go98] Other estimates, taking into account several published magnitude measurements and a large range of albedo assumptions, estimate a diameter range of 5.5 to 24.7 kilometers.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] 2014 SR339 is a member of the Apollo asteroids, which cross the orbit of Earth.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] Apollo's are the largest group of near-Earth objects with nearly 10 thousand known objects.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] It orbits the Sun at a distance of 0.90–1.70 AU once every 18 months (541 days; semi-major axis of 1.30 AU).
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] Its orbit has an eccentricity of 0.30 and an inclination of 30° with respect to the ecliptic.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] With an aphelion of 1.70 AU, it is also a Mars-crosser, as it crosses the orbit of the Red Planet at 1.666 AU.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] The body's observation arc begins with its official discovery observation by WISE in September 2014.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] As a potentially hazardous asteroid, 2014 SR339 has a minimum orbital intersection distance (MOID) with Earth of less than 0.05 AU and a diameter of greater than 150 meters.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] The Earth-MOID is currently 0.0354 AU (5,300,000 km), which translates into 13.8 lunar distances (LD).
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] On 7 February 2018 it passed 0.054 AU (21 LD) from the Earth when its apparent magnitude brightened to 14.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] Goldstone observed it until the following day.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] While this was an 8.1-million kilometer flyby, the next close flyby of 6.3 million km will occur on 5 February 2058, and another 7.6 million km on 8 February 2095.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] It will also have a 3.2 million km flyby of Mars on 26 September 2048.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] The asteroid's spectral type is unknown.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] Due to its unusually low albedo *(see below)* it is likely a carbonaceous C-type asteroid.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] On 9 February, radiometric observations by the Arecibo Observatory revealed that the asteroid has an elongated, lumpy shape.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] The radar images also gave it a rotational period between 8 and 9 hours.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] According to the survey carried out by the NEOWISE mission of NASA's WISE telescope, 2014 SR339 measures 0.971 kilometers in diameter and its surface has an albedo of 0.068.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] During its close approach in February 2018, radiometric observations by Arecibo Observatory determined that the object is at least 1.5 kilometers (0.93 miles) wide.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] Data from the Arecibo Telescope released in 2022 showed an unusually high radar albedo, possibly indicating rich metal content.
[src:asteroid/505657-2014-sr339] This minor planet was numbered by the Minor Planet Center on 4 November 2017 (M.P.C.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] An **asteroid** is a minor planet—an object larger than a meteoroid (thus 1 meter or larger) that is neither a planet nor an identified comet—that orbits within the inner Solar System or is co-orbital with Jupiter (Trojan asteroids).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Asteroids are rocky, metallic, or icy bodies with no atmosphere, and are broadly classified into C-type (carbonaceous), M-type (metallic), or S-type (silicaceous).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The size and shape of asteroids vary significantly, ranging from small rubble piles under a kilometer across to Ceres, a dwarf planet almost 1000 km in diameter.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] A body is classified as a comet, not an asteroid, if it shows a coma (tail) when warmed by solar radiation, although recent observations suggest a continuum between these types of bodies.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Of the roughly one million known asteroids, the greatest number are located between the orbits of Mars and Jupiter, approximately 2 to 4 astronomical units (AU) from the Sun, in a region known as the main asteroid belt.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The total mass of all the asteroids combined is only 3% that of Earth's Moon.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The majority of main belt asteroids follow slightly elliptical, stable orbits, revolving in the same direction as the Earth and taking from three to six years to complete a full orbit around the Sun.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Asteroids have been observed from Earth since their discovery in 1801.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The first close-up observation of an asteroid was made by the Galileo spacecraft.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Several dedicated missions to asteroids were subsequently launched by NASA and JAXA, with plans for other missions in progress.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] NASA's *NEAR Shoemaker* studied Eros, and *Dawn* observed Vesta and Ceres.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] JAXA's missions *Hayabusa* and *Hayabusa2* studied and returned samples of Itokawa and Ryugu, respectively.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] OSIRIS-REx studied Bennu, collecting a sample in 2020 which was delivered back to Earth in 2023.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] NASA's *Lucy*, launched in 2021, is tasked with studying ten different asteroids, two from the main belt and eight Jupiter trojans.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] NASA's Double Asteroid Redirection Test (DART), launched in 2021, was intentionally crashed into the non-threatening asteroid Dimorphos in September 2022 as a test of planetary defense technology.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] NASA's *Psyche*, launched October 2023, aims to study the metallic asteroid Psyche.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] ESA's *Hera*, launched in October 2024, is intended to study the results of the DART impact.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] CNSA's *Tianwen-2* was launched in May 2025, to explore the co-orbital near-Earth asteroid 469219 Kamoʻoalewa and the active asteroid 311P/PanSTARRS and collecting samples of the regolith of Kamo'oalewa.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Near-Earth asteroids have the potential for catastrophic consequences if they strike Earth, with a notable example being the Chicxulub impact, widely thought to have induced the Cretaceous–Paleogene mass extinction.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] A composite image, to the same scale, of the asteroids imaged at high resolution prior to 2012.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Historically, the first discovered asteroid, Ceres, was at first considered a new planet.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] It was followed by the discovery of other similar bodies, which with the equipment of the time appeared to be points of light like stars, showing little or no planetary disc, though readily distinguishable from stars due to their apparent motions.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] This prompted the astronomer Sir William Herschel to propose the term *asteroid*, coined in Greek as ἀστεροειδής, or *asteroeidēs*, meaning 'star-like, star-shaped', and derived from the Ancient Greek ἀστήρ *astēr* 'star, planet'.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In the early second half of the 19th century, the terms *asteroid* and *planet* (not always qualified as "minor") were still used interchangeably.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Traditionally, small bodies orbiting the Sun were classified as comets, asteroids, or meteoroids, with anything smaller than one meter across being called a meteoroid.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The term *asteroid,* never officially defined, can be informally used to mean "an irregularly shaped rocky body orbiting the Sun that does not qualify as a planet or a dwarf planet under the IAU definitions".
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The main difference between an asteroid and a comet is that a comet shows a coma (tail) due to sublimation of its near-surface ices by solar radiation.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] A few objects were first classified as minor planets but later showed evidence of cometary activity.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Conversely, some (perhaps all) comets are eventually depleted of their surface volatile ices and become asteroid-like.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] A further distinction is that comets typically have more eccentric orbits than most asteroids; highly eccentric asteroids are probably dormant or extinct comets.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The minor planets beyond Jupiter's orbit are sometimes also called "asteroids", especially in popular presentations.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] However, it is becoming increasingly common for the term *asteroid* to be restricted to minor planets of the inner Solar System.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Therefore, this article will restrict itself for the most part to the classical asteroids: objects of the asteroid belt, Jupiter trojans, and near-Earth objects.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] For almost two centuries after the discovery of Ceres in 1801, all known asteroids spent most of their time at or within the orbit of Jupiter, though a few, such as 944 Hidalgo, ventured farther for part of their orbit.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Starting in 1977 with 2060 Chiron, astronomers discovered small bodies that permanently resided further out than Jupiter, now called centaurs.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In 1992, 15760 Albion was discovered, the first object beyond the orbit of Neptune (other than Pluto); soon large numbers of similar objects were observed, now called trans-Neptunian objects.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Further out are Kuiper-belt objects, scattered-disc objects, and the much more distant Oort cloud, hypothesized to be the main reservoir of dormant comets.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The Kuiper-belt bodies are called "objects" partly to avoid the need to classify them as asteroids or comets.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] They are thought to be predominantly comet-like in composition, though some may be more akin to asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Most do not have the highly eccentric orbits associated with comets, and the ones so far discovered are larger than traditional comet nuclei.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Other recent observations, such as the analysis of the cometary dust collected by the *Stardust* probe, are increasingly blurring the distinction between comets and asteroids, suggesting "a continuum between asteroids and comets" rather than a sharp dividing line.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In 2006, the IAU created the class of dwarf planets for the largest minor planets—those massive enough to have become ellipsoidal under their own gravity.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Only the largest object in the asteroid belt has been placed in this category: Ceres, at about 975 km (606 mi) across.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Asteroids have been distinguished from the concept of planetoid by describing them respectively as undifferentiated and differentiated, like dwarf planets.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Despite their large numbers, asteroids are a relatively recent discovery, with the first one—Ceres—only being identified in 1801.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Only one asteroid, 4 Vesta, which has a relatively reflective surface, is normally visible to the naked eye in dark skies when it is favorably positioned.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Rarely, small asteroids passing close to Earth may be briefly visible to the naked eye.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] As of May 2025, the Minor Planet Center had data on 1,460,356 minor planets in the inner and outer Solar System, of which about 826,864 had enough information to be given numbered designations.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In 1772, German astronomer Johann Elert Bode, citing Johann Daniel Titius, published a numerical procession known as the Titius–Bode law (now discredited).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Except for an unexplained gap between Mars and Jupiter, Bode's formula seemed to predict the orbits of the known planets.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Bode's formula predicted another planet would be found with an orbital radius near 2.8 astronomical units (AU), or 420 million km, from the Sun.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The Titius–Bode law got a boost with William Herschel's discovery of Uranus near the predicted distance for a planet beyond Saturn.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Although they did not discover Ceres, they later found the asteroids 2 Pallas, 3 Juno and 4 Vesta.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] One of the astronomers selected for the search was Giuseppe Piazzi, a Catholic priest at the Academy of Palermo, Sicily.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Before receiving his invitation to join the group, Piazzi discovered Ceres on 1 January 1801.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] He was searching for "the 87th [star] of the Catalogue of the Zodiacal stars of Mr la Caille", but found that "it was preceded by another".
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Piazzi observed Ceres a total of 24 times, the final time on 11 February 1801, when illness interrupted his work.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] He announced his discovery on 24 January 1801 in letters to only two fellow astronomers, his compatriot Barnaba Oriani of Milan and Bode in Berlin.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] He reported it as a comet but "since its movement is so slow and rather uniform, it has occurred to me several times that it might be something better than a comet".
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In April, Piazzi sent his complete observations to Oriani, Bode, and French astronomer Jérôme Lalande.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The information was published in the September 1801 issue of the *Monatliche Correspondenz*.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] By this time, the apparent position of Ceres had changed (mostly due to Earth's motion around the Sun), and was too close to the Sun's glare for other astronomers to confirm Piazzi's observations.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Toward the end of the year, Ceres should have been visible again, but after such a long time it was difficult to predict its exact position.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] To recover Ceres, mathematician Carl Friedrich Gauss, then 24 years old, developed an efficient method of orbit determination.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In a few weeks, he predicted the path of Ceres and sent his results to von Zach.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] On 31 December 1801, von Zach and fellow celestial policeman Heinrich W.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Olbers found Ceres near the predicted position and thus recovered it.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] At 2.8 AU from the Sun, Ceres appeared to fit the Titius–Bode law almost perfectly; however, Neptune, once discovered in 1846, was 8 AU closer than predicted, leading most astronomers to conclude that the law was a coincidence.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Piazzi named the newly discovered object *Ceres Ferdinandea,* "in honor of the patron goddess of Sicily and of King Ferdinand of Bourbon".
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Three other asteroids (2 Pallas, 3 Juno, and 4 Vesta) were discovered by von Zach's group over the next few years, with Vesta found in 1807.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] No new asteroids were discovered until 1845.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Amateur astronomer Karl Ludwig Hencke started his searches of new asteroids in 1830, and fifteen years later, while looking for Vesta, he found the asteroid later named 5 Astraea.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] It was the first new asteroid discovery in 38 years.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Carl Friedrich Gauss was given the honor of naming the asteroid.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] After this, other astronomers joined; 15 asteroids were found by the end of 1851.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In 1868, when James Craig Watson discovered the 100th asteroid, the French Academy of Sciences engraved the faces of Karl Theodor Robert Luther, John Russell Hind, and Hermann Goldschmidt, the three most successful asteroid-hunters at that time, on a commemorative medallion marking the event.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In 1891, Max Wolf pioneered the use of astrophotography to detect asteroids, which appeared as short streaks on long-exposure photographic plates.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] This dramatically increased the rate of detection compared with earlier visual methods: Wolf alone discovered 248 asteroids, beginning with 323 Brucia, whereas only slightly more than 300 had been discovered up to that point.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] It was known that there were many more, but most astronomers did not bother with them, some calling them "vermin of the skies", a phrase variously attributed to Eduard Suess and Edmund Weiss.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Even a century later, only a few thousand asteroids were identified, numbered and named.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In the past, asteroids were discovered by a four-step process.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] First, a region of the sky was photographed by a wide-field telescope or astrograph.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Pairs of photographs were taken, typically one hour apart.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Multiple pairs could be taken over a series of days.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Second, the two films or plates of the same region were viewed under a stereoscope.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] A body in orbit around the Sun would move slightly between the pair of films.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Under the stereoscope, the image of the body would seem to float slightly above the background of stars.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Third, once a moving body was identified, its location would be measured precisely using a digitizing microscope.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The location would be measured relative to known star locations.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The last step is sending the locations and time of observations to the Minor Planet Center, where computer programs determine whether an apparition ties together earlier apparitions into a single orbit.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] If so, the object receives a catalogue number and the observer of the first apparition with a calculated orbit is declared the discoverer, and granted the honor of naming the object subject to the approval of the International Astronomical Union.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] By 1851, the Royal Astronomical Society decided that asteroids were being discovered at such a rapid rate that a different system was needed to categorize or name asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In 1852, when de Gasparis discovered the twentieth asteroid, Benjamin Valz gave it a name and a number designating its rank among asteroid discoveries, 20 Massalia.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Sometimes asteroids were discovered and not seen again.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] So, starting in 1892, new asteroids were listed by the year and a capital letter indicating the order in which the asteroid's orbit was calculated and registered within that specific year.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] For example, the first two asteroids discovered in 1892 were labeled 1892A and 1892B.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] However, there were not enough letters in the alphabet for all of the asteroids discovered in 1893, so 1893Z was followed by 1893AA.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] A number of variations of these methods were tried, including designations that included year plus a Greek letter in 1914.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] A simple chronological numbering system was established in 1925.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Currently all newly discovered asteroids receive a provisional designation (such as 2002 AT4) consisting of the year of discovery and an alphanumeric code indicating the half-month of discovery and the sequence within that half-month.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Once an asteroid's orbit has been confirmed, it is given a number, and later may also be given a name (e.g.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The formal naming convention uses parentheses around the number—e.g.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] (433) Eros—but dropping the parentheses is quite common.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Informally, it is also common to drop the number altogether, or to drop it after the first mention when a name is repeated in running text.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In addition, names can be proposed by the asteroid's discoverer, within guidelines established by the International Astronomical Union.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The first asteroids to be discovered were assigned iconic symbols like the ones traditionally used to designate the planets.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] By 1852 there were two dozen asteroid symbols, which often occurred in multiple variants.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In 1851, after the fifteenth asteroid, Eunomia, had been discovered, Johann Franz Encke made a major change in the upcoming 1854 edition of the *Berliner Astronomisches Jahrbuch* (BAJ, *Berlin Astronomical Yearbook*).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] He introduced a disk (circle), a traditional symbol for a star, as the generic symbol for an asteroid.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The circle was then numbered in order of discovery to indicate a specific asteroid.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The numbered-circle convention was quickly adopted by astronomers, and the next asteroid to be discovered (16 Psyche, in 1852) was the first to be designated in that way at the time of its discovery.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] However, Psyche was given an iconic symbol as well, as were a few other asteroids discovered over the next few years.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] 20 Massalia was the first asteroid that was not assigned an iconic symbol, and no iconic symbols were created after the 1855 discovery of 37 Fides.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Many asteroids are the shattered remnants of planetesimals, bodies within the young Sun's solar nebula that never grew large enough to become planets.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] It is thought that planetesimals in the asteroid belt evolved much like the rest of objects in the solar nebula until Jupiter neared its current mass, at which point excitation from orbital resonances with Jupiter ejected over 99% of planetesimals in the belt.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Simulations and a discontinuity in spin rate and spectral properties suggest that asteroids larger than approximately 120 km (75 mi) in diameter accreted during that early era, whereas smaller bodies are fragments from collisions between asteroids during or after the Jovian disruption.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Ceres and Vesta grew large enough to melt and differentiate, with heavy metallic elements sinking to the core, leaving rocky minerals in the crust.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In the Nice model, many Kuiper-belt objects are captured in the outer asteroid belt, at distances greater than 2.6 AU.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Most were later ejected by Jupiter, but those that remained may be the D-type asteroids, and possibly include Ceres.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Various dynamical groups of asteroids have been discovered orbiting in the inner Solar System.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Their orbits are perturbed by the gravity of other bodies in the Solar System and by the Yarkovsky effect.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The majority of known asteroids orbit within the asteroid belt between the orbits of Mars and Jupiter, generally in relatively low-eccentricity (i.e. not very elongated) orbits.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] This belt is estimated to contain between 1.1 and 1.9 million asteroids larger than 1 km (0.6 mi) in diameter, and millions of smaller ones.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] These asteroids may be remnants of the protoplanetary disk, and in this region the accretion of planetesimals into planets during the formative period of the Solar System was prevented by large gravitational perturbations by Jupiter.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Contrary to popular imagery, the asteroid belt is mostly empty.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The asteroids are spread over such a large volume that reaching an asteroid without aiming carefully would be improbable.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Nonetheless, hundreds of thousands of asteroids are currently known, and the total number ranges in the millions or more, depending on the lower size cutoff.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Over 200 asteroids are known to be larger than 100 km, and a survey in the infrared wavelengths has shown that the asteroid belt has between 700,000 and 1.7 million asteroids with a diameter of 1 km or more.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The absolute magnitudes of most of the known asteroids are between 11 and 19, with the median at about 16.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The total mass of the asteroid belt is estimated to be 2.39×1021 kg, which is just 3% of the mass of the Moon; the mass of the Kuiper Belt and Scattered Disk is over 100 times as large.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The four largest objects, Ceres, Vesta, Pallas, and Hygiea, account for maybe 62% of the belt's total mass, with 39% accounted for by Ceres alone.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Trojans are populations that share an orbit with a larger planet or moon, but do not collide with it because they orbit in one of the two Lagrangian points of stability, L4 and L5, which lie 60° ahead of and behind the larger body.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In the Solar System, most known trojans share the orbit of Jupiter.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] They are divided into the Greek camp at L4 (ahead of Jupiter) and the Trojan camp at L5 (trailing Jupiter).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] More than a million Jupiter trojans larger than one kilometer are thought to exist, of which more than 7,000 are currently catalogued.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In other planetary orbits only nine Mars trojans, 28 Neptune trojans, two Uranus trojans, and two Earth trojans, have been found to date.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Numerical orbital dynamics stability simulations indicate that Saturn and Uranus probably do not have any primordial trojans.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Near-Earth asteroids, or NEAs, are asteroids that have orbits that pass close to that of Earth.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Asteroids that actually cross Earth's orbital path are known as *Earth-crossers*.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] As of April 2022, a total of 28,772 near-Earth asteroids were known; 878 have a diameter of one kilometer or larger.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] A small number of NEAs are extinct comets that have lost their volatile surface materials, although having a faint or intermittent comet-like tail does not necessarily result in a classification as a near-Earth comet, making the boundaries somewhat fuzzy.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The rest of the near-Earth asteroids are driven out of the asteroid belt by gravitational interactions with Jupiter.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Many asteroids have natural satellites (minor-planet moons).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] As of October 2021, there were 85 NEAs known to have at least one moon, including three known to have two moons.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The asteroid 3122 Florence, one of the largest potentially hazardous asteroids with a diameter of 4.5 km (2.8 mi), has two moons measuring 100–300 m (330–980 ft) across, which were discovered by radar imaging during the asteroid's 2017 approach to Earth.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] It is unclear whether Martian moons Phobos and Deimos are captured asteroids or were formed due to impact event on Mars.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Phobos and Deimos both have much in common with carbonaceous C-type asteroids, with spectra, albedo, and density very similar to those of C- or D-type asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Based on their similarity, one hypothesis is that both moons may be captured main-belt asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Capture also requires dissipation of energy.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The current Martian atmosphere is too thin to capture a Phobos-sized object by atmospheric braking.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Landis has pointed out that the capture could have occurred if the original body was a binary asteroid that separated under tidal forces.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Phobos could be a second-generation Solar System object that coalesced in orbit after Mars formed, rather than forming concurrently out of the same birth cloud as Mars.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Another hypothesis is that Mars was once surrounded by many Phobos- and Deimos-sized bodies, perhaps ejected into orbit around it by a collision with a large planetesimal.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The high porosity of the interior of Phobos (based on the density of 1.88 g/cm3, voids are estimated to comprise 25 to 35 percent of Phobos's volume) is inconsistent with an asteroidal origin.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Observations of Phobos in the thermal infrared suggest a composition containing mainly phyllosilicates, which are well known from the surface of Mars.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The spectra are distinct from those of all classes of chondrite meteorites, again pointing away from an asteroidal origin.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Both sets of findings support an origin of Phobos from material ejected by an impact on Mars that reaccreted in Martian orbit, similar to the prevailing theory for the origin of Earth's moon.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] and the remainder of the Main Belt (pink).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Asteroids vary greatly in size, from almost 1,000 km (620 mi) for the largest down to rocks just 1 m (3.3 ft) across, below which an object is classified as a meteoroid.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The three largest are very much like miniature planets: they are roughly spherical, have at least partly differentiated interiors, and are thought to be surviving protoplanets.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The vast majority, however, are much smaller and are irregularly shaped; they are thought to be either battered planetesimals or fragments of larger bodies.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The dwarf planet Ceres is by far the largest asteroid, with a diameter of 940 km (580 mi).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The next largest are 4 Vesta and 2 Pallas, both with diameters of just over 500 km (300 mi).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Vesta is the brightest of the four main-belt asteroids that can, on occasion, be visible to the naked eye.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] On some rare occasions, a near-Earth asteroid may briefly become visible without technical aid; see 99942 Apophis.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The mass of all the objects of the asteroid belt, lying between the orbits of Mars and Jupiter, is estimated to be (2394±6)×1018 kg, ≈3.25% of the mass of the Moon.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Of this, Ceres comprises 938×1018 kg, about 40% of the total.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Adding in the next three most massive objects, Vesta (11%), Pallas (8.5%), and Hygiea (3–4%), brings this figure up to a bit over 60%, whereas the next seven most-massive asteroids bring the total up to 70%.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The number of asteroids increases rapidly as their individual masses decrease.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The number of asteroids decreases markedly with increasing size.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Although the size distribution generally follows a power law, there are 'bumps' at about 5 km and 100 km, where more asteroids than expected from such a curve are found.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Most asteroids larger than approximately 120 kilometres (75 mi) in diameter are primordial (surviving from the accretion epoch), whereas most smaller asteroids are products of fragmentation of primordial asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The primordial population of the main belt was probably 200 times what it is today.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Three largest objects in the asteroid belt, Ceres, Vesta, and Pallas, are intact protoplanets that share many characteristics common to planets, and are atypical compared to the majority of irregularly shaped asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The fourth-largest asteroid, Hygiea, appears nearly spherical although it may have an undifferentiated interior, like the majority of asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The four largest asteroids constitute about five-eighths of the mass of the asteroid belt; Ceres and Vesta alone constitute half.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Ceres is the only asteroid that appears to have a plastic shape under its own gravity and hence the only one that is a dwarf planet.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] It has a much higher absolute magnitude than the other asteroids, of around 3.32, and may possess a surface layer of ice.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Like the planets, Ceres is differentiated: it has a crust, a mantle and a core.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] No meteorites from Ceres have been found on Earth.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Vesta, too, has a differentiated interior, though it formed inside the Solar System's frost line, and so is devoid of water; its composition is mainly of basaltic rock with minerals such as olivine.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Aside from the large crater at its southern pole, Rheasilvia, Vesta also has an ellipsoidal shape.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Vesta is the parent body of the Vestian family and other V-type asteroids, and is the source of the HED meteorites, which constitute 5% of all meteorites on Earth.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Pallas is unusual in that, like Uranus, it rotates on its side, with its axis of rotation tilted at high angles to its orbital plane.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Its composition is similar to that of Ceres: high in carbon and silicon, and perhaps partially differentiated.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Pallas is the parent body of the Palladian family of asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Hygiea is the largest carbonaceous asteroid and, unlike the other largest asteroids, lies relatively close to the plane of the ecliptic.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] It is the largest member and presumed parent body of the Hygiean family of asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Because there is no sufficiently large crater on the surface to be the source of that family, as there is on Vesta, it is thought that Hygiea may have been completely disrupted in the collision that formed the Hygiean family and recoalesced after losing a bit less than 2% of its mass.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Observations taken with the Very Large Telescope's SPHERE imager in 2017 and 2018, revealed that Hygiea has a nearly spherical shape, which is consistent both with it being in hydrostatic equilibrium, or formerly being in hydrostatic equilibrium, or with being disrupted and recoalescing.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Internal differentiation of large asteroids is possibly related to their lack of natural satellites, as satellites of main belt asteroids are mostly believed to form from collisional disruption, creating a rubble pile structure.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Measurements of the rotation rates of large asteroids in the asteroid belt show that there is an upper limit.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Very few asteroids with a diameter larger than 100 meters have a rotation period less than 2.2 hours.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] For asteroids rotating faster than approximately this rate, the inertial force at the surface is greater than the gravitational force, so any loose surface material would be flung out.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] However, a solid object should be able to rotate much more rapidly.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] This suggests that most asteroids with a diameter over 100 meters are rubble piles formed through the accumulation of debris after collisions between asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Asteroids become darker and redder with age due to space weathering.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] However evidence suggests most of the color change occurs rapidly, in the first hundred thousand years, limiting the usefulness of spectral measurement for determining the age of asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Except for the "big four" (Ceres, Pallas, Vesta, and Hygiea), asteroids are likely to be broadly similar in appearance, if irregular in shape.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] 50 km (31 mi) 253 Mathilde is a rubble pile saturated with craters with diameters the size of the asteroid's radius.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Earth-based observations of 300 km (190 mi) 511 Davida, one of the largest asteroids after the big four, reveal a similarly angular profile, suggesting it is also saturated with radius-size craters.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Medium-sized asteroids such as Mathilde and 243 Ida, that have been observed up close, also reveal a deep regolith covering the surface.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Of the big four, Pallas and Hygiea are practically unknown.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Vesta has compression fractures encircling a radius-size crater at its south pole but is otherwise a spheroid.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Asteroids are classified by their characteristic emission spectra, with the majority falling into three main groups: C-type, M-type, and S-type.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] These describe carbonaceous (carbon-rich), metallic, and silicaceous (stony) compositions, respectively.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The physical composition of asteroids is varied and in most cases poorly understood.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Ceres appears to be composed of a rocky core covered by an icy mantle; Vesta is thought to have a nickel-iron core, olivine mantle, and basaltic crust.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Thought to be the largest undifferentiated asteroid, 10 Hygiea seems to have a uniformly primitive composition of carbonaceous chondrite, but it may actually be a differentiated asteroid that was globally disrupted by an impact and then reassembled.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Other asteroids appear to be the remnant cores or mantles of proto-planets, high in rock and metal.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Most small asteroids are believed to be piles of rubble held together loosely by gravity, although the largest are probably solid.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Some asteroids have moons or are co-orbiting binaries: rubble piles, moons, binaries, and scattered asteroid families are thought to be the results of collisions that disrupted a parent asteroid, or possibly a planet.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Within these populations, larger asteroids are denser, presumably due to compression.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] There appears to be minimal macro-porosity (interstitial vacuum) in the score of asteroids with masses greater than 10×1018 kg.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Composition is calculated from three primary sources: albedo, surface spectrum, and density.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The last can only be determined accurately by observing the orbits of moons the asteroid might have.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] So far, every asteroid with moons has turned out to be a rubble pile, a loose conglomeration of rock and metal that may be half empty space by volume.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The investigated asteroids are as large as 280 km in diameter, and include 121 Hermione (268×186×183 km), and 87 Sylvia (384×262×232 km).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Few asteroids are larger than 87 Sylvia, none of them have moons.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] This means that the cores of the planets could have formed relatively quickly.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Scientists hypothesize that some of the first water brought to Earth was delivered by asteroid impacts after the collision that produced the Moon.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In 2009, the presence of water ice was confirmed on the surface of 24 Themis using NASA's Infrared Telescope Facility.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The surface of the asteroid appears completely covered in ice.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] As this ice layer is sublimating, it may be getting replenished by a reservoir of ice under the surface.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Organic compounds were also detected on the surface.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The presence of ice on 24 Themis makes the initial theory plausible.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In October 2013, water was detected on an extrasolar body for the first time, on an asteroid orbiting the white dwarf GD 61.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] On 22 January 2014, European Space Agency (ESA) scientists reported the detection, for the first definitive time, of water vapor on Ceres, the largest object in the asteroid belt.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The detection was made by using the far-infrared abilities of the Herschel Space Observatory.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The finding is unexpected because comets, not asteroids, are typically considered to "sprout jets and plumes".
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Findings have shown that solar winds can react with the oxygen in the upper layer of the asteroids and create water.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] It has been estimated that "every cubic metre of irradiated rock could contain up to 20 litres"; study was conducted using an atom probe tomography, numbers are given for the Itokawa S-type asteroid.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Acfer 049, a meteorite discovered in Algeria in 1990, was shown in 2019 to have an ultraporous lithology (UPL): porous texture that could be formed by removal of ice that filled these pores, this suggests that UPL "represent fossils of primordial ice".
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Asteroids contain traces of amino acids and other organic compounds, and some speculate that asteroid impacts may have seeded the early Earth with the chemicals necessary to initiate life, or may have even brought life itself to Earth (an event called "panspermia").
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In August 2011, a report, based on NASA studies with meteorites found on Earth, was published suggesting DNA and RNA components (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) may have been formed on asteroids and comets in outer space.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Asteroids are commonly categorized according to two criteria: the characteristics of their orbits, and features of their reflectance spectrum.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Many asteroids have been placed in groups and families based on their orbital characteristics.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Apart from the broadest divisions, it is customary to name a group of asteroids after the first member of that group to be discovered.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Groups are relatively loose dynamical associations, whereas families are tighter and result from the catastrophic break-up of a large parent asteroid sometime in the past.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Families are more common and easier to identify within the main asteroid belt, but several small families have been reported among the Jupiter trojans.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Main belt families were first recognized by Kiyotsugu Hirayama in 1918 and are often called Hirayama families in his honor.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] About 30–35% of the bodies in the asteroid belt belong to dynamical families, each thought to have a common origin in a past collision between asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] A family has also been associated with the plutoid dwarf planet Haumea.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Some asteroids have unusual horseshoe orbits that are co-orbital with Earth or another planet.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Examples are 3753 Cruithne and 2002 AA29.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The first instance of this type of orbital arrangement was discovered between Saturn's moons Epimetheus and Janus.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Sometimes these horseshoe objects temporarily become quasi-satellites for a few decades or a few hundred years, before returning to their earlier status.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Both Earth and Venus are known to have quasi-satellites.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Such objects, if associated with Earth or Venus or even hypothetically Mercury, are a special class of Aten asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] However, such objects could be associated with the outer planets as well.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In 1975, an asteroid taxonomic system based on color, albedo, and spectral shape was developed by Chapman, Morrison, and Zellner.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] These properties are thought to correspond to the composition of the asteroid's surface material.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The original classification system had three categories: C-types for dark carbonaceous objects (75% of known asteroids), S-types for stony (silicaceous) objects (17% of known asteroids) and U for those that did not fit into either C or S.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] This classification has since been expanded to include many other asteroid types.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The number of types continues to grow as more asteroids are studied.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The two most widely used taxonomies now used are the Tholen classification and SMASS classification.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The former was proposed in 1984 by David J.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Tholen, and was based on data collected from an eight-color asteroid survey performed in the 1980s.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] This resulted in 14 asteroid categories.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] In 2002, the Small Main-Belt Asteroid Spectroscopic Survey resulted in a modified version of the Tholen taxonomy with 24 different types.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Both systems have three broad categories of C, S, and X asteroids, where X consists of mostly metallic asteroids, such as the M-type.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The proportion of known asteroids falling into the various spectral types does not necessarily reflect the proportion of all asteroids that are of that type; some types are easier to detect than others, biasing the totals.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Originally, spectral designations were based on inferences of an asteroid's composition.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] However, the correspondence between spectral class and composition is not always very good, and a variety of classifications are in use.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Although asteroids of different spectral classifications are likely to be composed of different materials, there are no assurances that asteroids within the same taxonomic class are composed of the same (or similar) materials.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Active asteroids are objects that have asteroid-like orbits but show comet-like visual characteristics.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] That is, they show comae, tails, or other visual evidence of mass-loss (like a comet), but their orbit remains within Jupiter's orbit (like an asteroid).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] These bodies were originally designated **main-belt comets** (MBCs) in 2006 by astronomers David C.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Jewitt and Henry Hsieh, but this name implies they are necessarily icy in composition like a comet and that they only exist within the main-belt, whereas the growing population of active asteroids shows that this is not always the case.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The first active asteroid discovered is 7968 Elst–Pizarro.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] It was discovered (as an asteroid) in 1979 but then was found to have a tail by Eric Elst and Guido Pizarro in 1996 and given the cometary designation 133P/Elst-Pizarro.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Another notable object is 311P/PanSTARRS: observations made by the Hubble Space Telescope revealed that it had six comet-like tails.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The tails are suspected to be streams of material ejected by the asteroid as a result of a rubble pile asteroid spinning fast enough to remove material from it.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] By smashing into the asteroid Dimorphos, NASA's Double Asteroid Redirection Test spacecraft made it an active asteroid.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Scientists had proposed that some active asteroids are the result of impact events, but no one had ever observed the activation of an asteroid.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The DART mission activated Dimorphos under precisely known and carefully observed impact conditions, enabling the detailed study of the formation of an active asteroid for the first time.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Observations show that Dimorphos lost approximately 1 million kilograms after the collision.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] Impact produced a dust plume that temporarily brightened the Didymos system and developed a 10,000-kilometer (6,200 mi)-long dust tail that persisted for several months.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] First identified in 2024, dark comets are asteroids that show non-gravitational acceleration, a behavior normally seen in comets but not asteroids, but have no coma or tail, appearing visually as asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The Outer Family consists of objects larger than 100 meters, and have orbits that reach out nearly to Jupiter, resembling Jupiter family comets.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] The Inner Family dark comets were smaller than 50 meters, darker, and had roughly circular orbits.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p01] All dark comets orbit in the main asteroid belt except for ʻOumuamua, an interstellar object, which was the first asteroid-like object to show non-gravitation acceleration, while appearing visually as an asteroid.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Until the age of space travel, objects in the asteroid belt could only be observed with large telescopes, their shapes and terrain remaining a mystery.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] The best modern ground-based telescopes and the Earth-orbiting Hubble Space Telescope can only resolve a small amount of detail on the surfaces of the largest asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Limited information about the shapes and compositions of asteroids can be inferred from their light curves (variation in brightness during rotation) and their spectral properties.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Sizes can be estimated by timing the lengths of star occultations (when an asteroid passes directly in front of a star).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Radar imaging can yield good information about asteroid shapes and orbital and rotational parameters, especially for near-Earth asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Spacecraft flybys can provide much more data than any ground or space-based observations; sample-return missions gives insights about regolith composition.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] As asteroids are rather small and faint objects, the data that can be obtained from ground-based observations (GBO) are limited.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] By means of ground-based optical telescopes the visual magnitude can be obtained; when converted into the absolute magnitude it gives a rough estimate of the asteroid's size.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Light-curve measurements can also be made by GBO; when collected over a long period of time it allows an estimate of the rotational period, the pole orientation (sometimes), and a rough estimate of the asteroid's shape.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Spectral data (both visible-light and near-infrared spectroscopy) gives information about the object's composition, used to classify the observed asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Such observations are limited as they provide information about only the thin layer on the surface (up to several micrometers).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Near-Earth asteroids that come into close vicinity of the planet can be studied in more details with radar; it provides information about the surface of the asteroid (for example can show the presence of craters and boulders).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Such observations were conducted by the Arecibo Observatory in Puerto Rico (305 meter dish) and Goldstone Observatory in California (70 meter dish).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Radar observations can also be used for accurate determination of the orbital and rotational dynamics of observed objects.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Both space and ground-based observatories conducted asteroid search programs; the space-based searches are expected to detect more objects because there is no atmosphere to interfere and because they can observe larger portions of the sky.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] NEOWISE observed more than 100,000 asteroids of the main belt, Spitzer Space Telescope observed more than 700 near-Earth asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] These observations determined rough sizes of the majority of observed objects, but provided limited detail about surface properties (such as regolith depth and composition, angle of repose, cohesion, and porosity).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Asteroids were also studied by the Hubble Space Telescope, such as tracking the colliding asteroids in the main belt, break-up of an asteroid, observing an active asteroid with six comet-like tails, and observing asteroids that were chosen as targets of dedicated missions.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] The first asteroid to be photographed in close-up was 951 Gaspra in 1991, followed in 1993 by 243 Ida and its moon Dactyl, all of which were imaged by the *Galileo* probe en route to Jupiter.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] The first dedicated asteroid probe was NASA's *NEAR Shoemaker*, which photographed 253 Mathilde in 1997, before entering into orbit around 433 Eros, finally landing on its surface in 2001.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] It was the first spacecraft to successfully orbit and land on an asteroid.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] From September to November 2005, the Japanese *Hayabusa* probe studied 25143 Itokawa in detail and returned samples of its surface to Earth on 13 June 2010, the first asteroid sample-return mission.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] In 2007, NASA launched the *Dawn* spacecraft, which orbited 4 Vesta for a year, and observed the dwarf planet Ceres for three years.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] NASA launched the OSIRIS-REx in 2016, a sample return mission to asteroid 101955 Bennu.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] In 2021, the probe departed the asteroid with a sample from its surface.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Sample was delivered to Earth in September 2023.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] The spacecraft continues its extended mission, designated OSIRIS-APEX, to explore near-Earth asteroid Apophis in 2029.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] In 2021, NASA launched Double Asteroid Redirection Test (DART), a mission to test technology for defending Earth against potential hazardous objects.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] DART deliberately crashed into the minor-planet moon Dimorphos of the double asteroid Didymos in September 2022 to assess the potential of a spacecraft impact to deflect an asteroid from a collision course with Earth.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] In October, NASA declared DART a success, confirming it had shortened Dimorphos's orbital period around Didymos by about 32 minutes.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] NASA's *Lucy*, launched in 2021, is a multiple-asteroid flyby probe focused on flying by 7 Jupiter trojans of varying types.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] While not yet set to reach its first main target, 3548 Eurybates, until 2027, it has made flybys of the main-belt asteroids 152830 Dinkinesh and 52246 Donaldjohanson.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] NASA's *Psyche*, launched in October 2023, is intended to study the large metallic asteroid of the same name, and is on track to arrive there in 2029.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] ESA's *Hera*, launched in October 2024, is intended study the results of the DART impact.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] It is expected to measure the size and morphology of the crater, and momentum transmitted by the impact, to determine the efficiency of the deflection produced by DART.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] CNSA's *Tianwen-2* was launched in May 2025.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] It will use solar electric propulsion to explore the co-orbital near-Earth asteroid 469219 Kamoʻoalewa and the active asteroid 311P/PanSTARRS.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] The spacecraft is tasked with collecting samples of the regolith of Kamo'oalewa.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] The concept of asteroid mining was proposed in the 1970s.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Matt Anderson defines successful asteroid mining as "the development of a mining program that is both financially self-sustaining and profitable to its investors".
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] It has been suggested that asteroids might be used as a source of materials that may be rare or exhausted on Earth, or materials for constructing space habitats.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Materials that are heavy and expensive to launch from Earth may someday be mined from asteroids and used for space manufacturing and construction.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] As resource depletion on Earth becomes more real, the idea of extracting valuable elements from asteroids and returning these to Earth for profit, or using space-based resources to build solar-power satellites and space habitats, becomes more attractive.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Hypothetically, water processed from ice could refuel orbiting propellant depots.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] From the astrobiological perspective, asteroid prospecting could provide scientific data for the search for extraterrestrial intelligence (SETI).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Some astrophysicists have suggested that if advanced extraterrestrial civilizations employed asteroid mining long ago, the hallmarks of these activities might be detectable.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] There is increasing interest in identifying asteroids whose orbits cross Earth's, and that could, given enough time, collide with Earth.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] The three most important groups of near-Earth asteroids are the Apollos, Amors, and Atens.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] The near-Earth asteroid 433 Eros had been discovered as long ago as 1898, and the 1930s brought a flurry of similar objects.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] In order of discovery, these were: 1221 Amor, 1862 Apollo, 2101 Adonis, and finally 69230 Hermes, which approached within 0.005 AU of Earth in 1937.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Astronomers began to realize the possibilities of Earth impact.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Two events in later decades increased the alarm: the increasing acceptance of the Alvarez hypothesis that an impact event resulted in the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction, and the 1994 observation of Comet Shoemaker-Levy 9 crashing into Jupiter.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] The U.S. military also declassified the information that its military satellites, built to detect nuclear explosions, had detected hundreds of upper-atmosphere impacts by objects ranging from one to ten meters across.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] All of these considerations helped spur the launch of highly efficient surveys, consisting of charge-coupled device (CCD) cameras and computers directly connected to telescopes.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] As of 2011, it was estimated that 89% to 96% of near-Earth asteroids one kilometer or larger in diameter had been discovered.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] As of 29 October 2018, the LINEAR system alone had discovered 147,132 asteroids.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Among the surveys, 19,266 near-Earth asteroids have been discovered including almost 900 more than 1 km (0.6 mi) in diameter.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] In June 2018, the National Science and Technology Council warned that the United States is unprepared for an asteroid impact event, and has developed and released the "National Near-Earth Object Preparedness Strategy Action Plan" to better prepare.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] According to expert testimony in the United States Congress in 2013, NASA would require at least five years of preparation before a mission to intercept an asteroid could be launched.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Various collision avoidance techniques have different trade-offs with respect to metrics such as overall performance, cost, failure risks, operations, and technology readiness.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] There are various methods for changing the course of an asteroid/comet.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] These can be differentiated by various types of attributes such as the type of mitigation (deflection or fragmentation), energy source (kinetic, electromagnetic, gravitational, solar/thermal, or nuclear), and approach strategy (interception, rendezvous, or remote station).
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Strategies fall into two basic sets: fragmentation and delay.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Fragmentation concentrates on rendering the impactor harmless by fragmenting it and scattering the fragments so that they miss the Earth or are small enough to burn up in the atmosphere.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Delay exploits the fact that both the Earth and the impactor are in orbit.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] An impact occurs when both reach the same point in space at the same time, or more correctly when some point on Earth's surface intersects the impactor's orbit when the impactor arrives.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Since the Earth is approximately 12,750 km (7,920 mi) in diameter and moves at approx.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] 30 km/s (19 mi/s) in its orbit, it travels a distance of one planetary diameter in about 425 seconds, or slightly over seven minutes.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Delaying, or advancing the impactor's arrival by times of this magnitude can, depending on the exact geometry of the impact, cause it to miss the Earth.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] "Project Icarus" was one of the first projects designed in 1967 as a contingency plan in case of collision with 1566 Icarus.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] The plan relied on the new Saturn V rocket, which did not make its first flight until after the report had been completed.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Six Saturn V rockets would be used, each launched at variable intervals from months to hours away from impact.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Each rocket was to be fitted with a single 100-megaton nuclear warhead as well as a modified Apollo Service Module and uncrewed Apollo Command Module for guidance to the target.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] The warheads would be detonated 30 meters from the surface, deflecting or partially destroying the asteroid.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Depending on the subsequent impacts on the course or the destruction of the asteroid, later missions would be modified or cancelled as needed.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] The "last-ditch" launch of the sixth rocket would be 18 hours prior to impact.
[src:asteroid/asteroid-p02] Asteroids and the asteroid belt are a staple of science fiction stories.
